WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:07.300 --> 00:00:08.500
PROFESSOR: Hi.

00:00:08.500 --> 00:00:10.380
Well, today's the chain rule.

00:00:10.380 --> 00:00:15.630
Very, very useful rule, and it's
kind of neat, natural.

00:00:15.630 --> 00:00:18.650
Can I explain what a chain
of functions is?

00:00:18.650 --> 00:00:21.810
There is a chain of functions.

00:00:21.810 --> 00:00:26.360
And then we want to know the
slope, the derivative.

00:00:26.360 --> 00:00:28.600
So how does the chain work?

00:00:28.600 --> 00:00:32.250
So there x is the input.

00:00:32.250 --> 00:00:35.000
It goes into a function
g of x.

00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:39.000
We could call that inside
function y.

00:00:39.000 --> 00:00:46.290
So the first step
is y is g of x.

00:00:46.290 --> 00:00:51.690
So we get an output
from g, call it y.

00:00:51.690 --> 00:00:57.250
That's halfway, because that y
then becomes the input to f.

00:00:57.250 --> 00:00:59.160
That completes the chain.

00:00:59.160 --> 00:01:03.850
It starts with x, produces
y, which is the inside

00:01:03.850 --> 00:01:05.470
function g of x.

00:01:05.470 --> 00:01:09.830
And then let me call
it z is f of y.

00:01:09.830 --> 00:01:13.870
And what I want to know
is how quickly does

00:01:13.870 --> 00:01:16.920
z change as x changes?

00:01:16.920 --> 00:01:18.740
That's what the chain
rule asks.

00:01:18.740 --> 00:01:22.260
It's the slope of that chain.

00:01:22.260 --> 00:01:24.900
Can I maybe just tell
you the chain rule?

00:01:24.900 --> 00:01:27.970
And then we'll try it
on some examples.

00:01:27.970 --> 00:01:30.170
You'll see how it works.

00:01:30.170 --> 00:01:32.120
OK, here it is.

00:01:32.120 --> 00:01:44.180
The derivative, the slope of
this chain dz dx, notice I

00:01:44.180 --> 00:01:47.830
want the change in the whole
thing when I change the

00:01:47.830 --> 00:01:49.530
original input.

00:01:49.530 --> 00:01:54.040
Then the formula is that
I take-- it's nice.

00:01:54.040 --> 00:02:04.800
You take dz dy times dy dx.

00:02:04.800 --> 00:02:08.539
So the derivative that we're
looking for, the slope, the

00:02:08.539 --> 00:02:14.160
speed, is a product of two
simpler derivatives that we

00:02:14.160 --> 00:02:16.200
probably know.

00:02:16.200 --> 00:02:20.100
And when we put the chain
together, we multiply those

00:02:20.100 --> 00:02:21.460
derivatives.

00:02:21.460 --> 00:02:28.310
But there's one catch
that I'll explain.

00:02:28.310 --> 00:02:31.620
I can give you a hint
right away.

00:02:31.620 --> 00:02:38.710
dz dy, this first factor,
depends on y.

00:02:38.710 --> 00:02:43.170
But we're looking for the change
due to the original

00:02:43.170 --> 00:02:46.150
change in x.

00:02:46.150 --> 00:02:51.110
When I find dz dy, I'm going
to have to get back to x.

00:02:51.110 --> 00:02:54.180
Let me just do an example
with a picture.

00:02:54.180 --> 00:02:56.480
You'll see why I
have to do it.

00:02:56.480 --> 00:03:02.350
So let the chain be cosine
of-- oh, sine.

00:03:02.350 --> 00:03:02.940
Why not?

00:03:02.940 --> 00:03:04.520
Sine of 3x.

00:03:04.520 --> 00:03:07.500
Let me take sine of 3x.

00:03:07.500 --> 00:03:15.520
So that's my sine of 3x.

00:03:15.520 --> 00:03:19.405
I would like to know if that's
my function, and I can draw it

00:03:19.405 --> 00:03:23.700
and will draw it, what
is the slope?

00:03:23.700 --> 00:03:26.720
OK, so what's the
inside function?

00:03:26.720 --> 00:03:28.340
What's y here?

00:03:28.340 --> 00:03:30.420
Well, it's sitting there
in parentheses.

00:03:30.420 --> 00:03:33.740
Often it's in parentheses so
we identify it right away.

00:03:33.740 --> 00:03:35.790
y is 3x.

00:03:35.790 --> 00:03:37.590
That's the inside function.

00:03:37.590 --> 00:03:40.775
And then the outside function
is the sine of y.

00:03:44.870 --> 00:03:47.330
So what's the derivative
by the chain rule?

00:03:47.330 --> 00:03:49.810
I'm ready to use the chain rule,
because these are such

00:03:49.810 --> 00:03:53.630
simple functions, I know their
separate derivative.

00:03:53.630 --> 00:03:57.230
So if this whole thing
is z, the chain rule

00:03:57.230 --> 00:04:03.780
says that dz dx is--

00:04:03.780 --> 00:04:05.000
I'm using this rule.

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:09.040
I first name dz dy, the
derivative of z with respect

00:04:09.040 --> 00:04:13.820
to y, which is cosine of y.

00:04:13.820 --> 00:04:17.560
And then the second factor is
dy dx, and that's just a

00:04:17.560 --> 00:04:22.820
straight line with slope
3, so dy dx is 3.

00:04:22.820 --> 00:04:24.580
Good.

00:04:24.580 --> 00:04:29.190
Good, but not finished, because
I'm getting an answer

00:04:29.190 --> 00:04:32.530
that's still in terms of y, and
I have to get back to x,

00:04:32.530 --> 00:04:34.430
and no problem to do it.

00:04:34.430 --> 00:04:36.750
I know the link from y to x.

00:04:36.750 --> 00:04:38.630
So here's the 3.

00:04:38.630 --> 00:04:41.550
I can usually write it out here,
and then I wouldn't need

00:04:41.550 --> 00:04:42.550
parentheses.

00:04:42.550 --> 00:04:44.250
That's just that 3.

00:04:44.250 --> 00:04:48.520
Now the part I'm caring
about: cosine of 3x.

00:04:52.900 --> 00:04:57.000
Not cosine x, even though
this was just sine.

00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:00.870
But it was sine of y, and
therefore, we need cosine 3x.

00:05:00.870 --> 00:05:05.480
Let me draw a picture of this
function, and you'll see

00:05:05.480 --> 00:05:08.420
what's going on.

00:05:08.420 --> 00:05:10.580
If I draw a picture of--

00:05:10.580 --> 00:05:15.570
I'll start with a picture of
sine x, maybe out to 180

00:05:15.570 --> 00:05:18.310
degrees pi.

00:05:18.310 --> 00:05:21.140
This direction is now x.

00:05:21.140 --> 00:05:25.000
And this direction is going to
be-- well, there is the sine

00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:27.500
of x, but that's not
my function.

00:05:27.500 --> 00:05:32.800
My function is sine of 3x, and
it's worth realizing what's

00:05:32.800 --> 00:05:33.750
the difference.

00:05:33.750 --> 00:05:39.720
How does the graph change if
I have 3x instead of x?

00:05:39.720 --> 00:05:42.420
Well, things come sooner.

00:05:42.420 --> 00:05:45.310
Things are speeded up.

00:05:45.310 --> 00:05:49.680
Here at x equal pi, 180 degrees,
is when the sine

00:05:49.680 --> 00:05:51.360
goes back to 0.

00:05:51.360 --> 00:05:56.510
But for 3x, it'll be back to
0 already when x is 60

00:05:56.510 --> 00:05:58.290
degrees, pi over 3.

00:05:58.290 --> 00:06:05.520
So 1/3 of the way along, right
there, my sine 3x is this one.

00:06:05.520 --> 00:06:11.700
It's just like the sine
curve but faster.

00:06:11.700 --> 00:06:15.940
That was pi over 3 there,
60 degrees.

00:06:15.940 --> 00:06:23.080
So this is my z of x curve, and
you can see that the slope

00:06:23.080 --> 00:06:26.220
is steeper at the beginning.

00:06:26.220 --> 00:06:27.890
You can see that the slope--

00:06:27.890 --> 00:06:30.700
things are happening
three times faster.

00:06:30.700 --> 00:06:33.200
Things are compressed by 3.

00:06:33.200 --> 00:06:37.300
This sine curve is
compressed by 3.

00:06:37.300 --> 00:06:44.190
That makes it speed up so the
slope is 3 at the start, and I

00:06:44.190 --> 00:06:47.300
claim that it's 3
cosine of 3x.

00:06:47.300 --> 00:06:49.320
Oh, let's draw the slope.

00:06:49.320 --> 00:06:52.350
All right, draw the slope.

00:06:52.350 --> 00:06:55.140
All right, let me start with
the slope of sine-- so this

00:06:55.140 --> 00:06:58.280
was just old sine x.

00:06:58.280 --> 00:07:04.400
So its slope is just
cosine x along to--

00:07:04.400 --> 00:07:04.980
right?

00:07:04.980 --> 00:07:11.850
That's the slope starts at 1.

00:07:11.850 --> 00:07:14.560
This is now cosine x.

00:07:14.560 --> 00:07:18.290
But that's going out
to pi again.

00:07:18.290 --> 00:07:21.050
That's the slope of the original
one, not the slope of

00:07:21.050 --> 00:07:23.660
our function, of our chain.

00:07:23.660 --> 00:07:27.290
So the slope of our
chain will be--

00:07:27.290 --> 00:07:29.160
I mean, it doesn't
go out so far.

00:07:29.160 --> 00:07:35.500
It's all between here and
pi over 3, right?

00:07:35.500 --> 00:07:38.580
Our function, the one
we're looking at, is

00:07:38.580 --> 00:07:40.680
just on this part.

00:07:40.680 --> 00:07:45.690
And the slope starts out at 3,
and it's three times bigger,

00:07:45.690 --> 00:07:47.760
so it's going to be--
well, I'll just

00:07:47.760 --> 00:07:49.200
about get it on there.

00:07:49.200 --> 00:07:50.450
It's going to go down.

00:07:54.980 --> 00:07:58.880
I don't know if that's great,
but it maybe makes the point

00:07:58.880 --> 00:08:05.700
that I started up here at 3, and
I ended down here at minus

00:08:05.700 --> 00:08:12.840
3 when x was 60 degrees
because then--

00:08:12.840 --> 00:08:18.830
you see, this is a picture
of 3 cosine of 3x.

00:08:21.410 --> 00:08:27.270
I had to replace y by
3x at this point.

00:08:27.270 --> 00:08:32.039
OK, let me do two or three
more examples,

00:08:32.039 --> 00:08:33.929
just so you see it.

00:08:33.929 --> 00:08:36.620
Let's take an easy one.

00:08:36.620 --> 00:08:42.510
Suppose z is x cubed squared.

00:08:45.170 --> 00:08:47.500
All right, here is the
inside function.

00:08:47.500 --> 00:08:54.350
y is x cubed, and z is--
do you see what z is?

00:08:54.350 --> 00:08:58.890
z is x cubed squared.

00:08:58.890 --> 00:09:02.080
So x cubed is the
inside function.

00:09:02.080 --> 00:09:04.910
What's the outside function?

00:09:04.910 --> 00:09:06.220
It's a function of y.

00:09:06.220 --> 00:09:07.400
I'm not going to write--

00:09:07.400 --> 00:09:10.020
it's going to be the
squaring function.

00:09:10.020 --> 00:09:11.710
That's what we do outside.

00:09:11.710 --> 00:09:13.610
I'm not going to write
x squared.

00:09:13.610 --> 00:09:15.310
It's y squared.

00:09:15.310 --> 00:09:16.170
This is y.

00:09:16.170 --> 00:09:18.380
It's y squared that
gets squared.

00:09:18.380 --> 00:09:26.010
Then the derivative dz dx by
the chain rule is dz dy.

00:09:26.010 --> 00:09:27.640
Shall I remember
the chain rule?

00:09:27.640 --> 00:09:32.350
dz dy, dy dx.

00:09:32.350 --> 00:09:37.810
Easy to remember because in the
mind of everybody, these

00:09:37.810 --> 00:09:42.530
dy's, you see that they're
sort of canceling.

00:09:42.530 --> 00:09:45.100
So what's dz dy?

00:09:45.100 --> 00:09:49.300
z is y squared, so this
is 2y, that factor.

00:09:49.300 --> 00:09:51.320
What's dy dx?

00:09:51.320 --> 00:09:52.650
y is x cubed.

00:09:52.650 --> 00:09:54.740
We know the derivative
of x cubed.

00:09:54.740 --> 00:09:58.050
It's 3x squared.

00:09:58.050 --> 00:10:04.210
There is the answer, but it's
not final because I've got a y

00:10:04.210 --> 00:10:05.830
here that doesn't belong.

00:10:05.830 --> 00:10:07.130
I've got to get it back to.

00:10:07.130 --> 00:10:12.630
X So I have all together 2 times
3 is making 6, and that

00:10:12.630 --> 00:10:17.420
y, I have to go back and see
what was y in terms of x.

00:10:17.420 --> 00:10:18.950
It was x cubed.

00:10:18.950 --> 00:10:22.150
So I have x cubed there, and
here's an x squared,

00:10:22.150 --> 00:10:25.460
altogether x to the fifth.

00:10:25.460 --> 00:10:28.340
Now, is that the right answer?

00:10:28.340 --> 00:10:33.110
In this example, we can
certainly check it because we

00:10:33.110 --> 00:10:37.350
know what x cubed squared is.

00:10:37.350 --> 00:10:42.430
So x cubed is x times x times
x, and I'm squaring that.

00:10:42.430 --> 00:10:43.850
I'm multiplying by itself.

00:10:43.850 --> 00:10:45.820
There's another x
times x times x.

00:10:45.820 --> 00:10:52.360
Altogether I have x to
the sixth power.

00:10:52.360 --> 00:10:54.230
Notice I don't add those.

00:10:54.230 --> 00:10:59.990
When I'm squaring x cubed,
I multiply the 2 by

00:10:59.990 --> 00:11:02.310
the 3 and get 6.

00:11:02.310 --> 00:11:06.040
So z is x to the sixth, and of
course, the derivative of x to

00:11:06.040 --> 00:11:10.390
the sixth is 6 times x to the
fifth, one power lower.

00:11:14.170 --> 00:11:17.630
OK, I want to do two
more examples.

00:11:17.630 --> 00:11:23.600
Let me do one more right away
while we're on a roll.

00:11:23.600 --> 00:11:30.310
I'll bring down that board and
take this function, just so

00:11:30.310 --> 00:11:32.580
you can spot the
inside function

00:11:32.580 --> 00:11:34.070
and the outside function.

00:11:34.070 --> 00:11:39.760
So my function z is going to be
1 over the square root of 1

00:11:39.760 --> 00:11:43.490
minus x squared.

00:11:43.490 --> 00:11:47.480
Such things come up pretty often
so we have to know its

00:11:47.480 --> 00:11:47.950
derivative.

00:11:47.950 --> 00:11:50.640
We could graph it.

00:11:50.640 --> 00:11:55.920
That's a perfectly reasonable
function, and

00:11:55.920 --> 00:11:59.100
it's a perfect chain.

00:11:59.100 --> 00:12:03.610
The first point is to identify
what's the inside function and

00:12:03.610 --> 00:12:04.950
what's the outside.

00:12:04.950 --> 00:12:08.370
So inside I'm seeing this
1 minus x squared.

00:12:08.370 --> 00:12:14.440
That's the quantity that it'll
be much simpler if I just give

00:12:14.440 --> 00:12:17.330
that a single name y.

00:12:17.330 --> 00:12:19.150
And then what's the
outside function?

00:12:19.150 --> 00:12:21.290
What am I doing to this y?

00:12:21.290 --> 00:12:26.480
I'm taking its square root,
so I have y to the 1/2.

00:12:26.480 --> 00:12:29.870
But that square root is
in the denominator.

00:12:29.870 --> 00:12:33.520
I'm dividing, so it's
y to the minus 1/2.

00:12:33.520 --> 00:12:38.800
So z is y to the minus 1/2.

00:12:38.800 --> 00:12:42.150
OK, those are functions I'm
totally happy with.

00:12:42.150 --> 00:12:44.355
The derivative is what?

00:12:48.310 --> 00:12:51.210
dz dy, I won't repeat
the chain rule.

00:12:51.210 --> 00:12:53.090
You've got that clearly
in mind.

00:12:53.090 --> 00:12:54.490
It's right above.

00:12:54.490 --> 00:12:56.970
Let's just put in
the answer here.

00:12:56.970 --> 00:13:01.140
dz dy, the derivative, that's
y to some power, so I get

00:13:01.140 --> 00:13:05.306
minus 1/2 times y
to what power?

00:13:08.210 --> 00:13:10.560
I always go one power lower.

00:13:10.560 --> 00:13:12.355
Here the power is minus 1/2.

00:13:12.355 --> 00:13:17.490
If I go down by one, I'll
have minus 3/2.

00:13:17.490 --> 00:13:22.630
And then I have to have
dy dx, which is easy.

00:13:22.630 --> 00:13:25.430
dy dx, y is 1 minus x squared.

00:13:25.430 --> 00:13:31.030
The derivative of that
is just minus 2x.

00:13:31.030 --> 00:13:37.490
And now I have to assemble
these, put them together, and

00:13:37.490 --> 00:13:39.660
get rid of the y.

00:13:39.660 --> 00:13:42.490
So the minus 2 cancels
the minus 1/2.

00:13:42.490 --> 00:13:43.600
That's nice.

00:13:43.600 --> 00:13:50.560
I have an x still here, and
I have y to the minus 3/2.

00:13:50.560 --> 00:13:52.310
What's that?

00:13:52.310 --> 00:13:58.660
I know what y is, 1 minus x
squared, and so it's that to

00:13:58.660 --> 00:14:01.220
the minus 3/2.

00:14:01.220 --> 00:14:02.760
I could write it that way.

00:14:02.760 --> 00:14:05.960
x times 1 minus x squared--

00:14:05.960 --> 00:14:07.410
that's the y--

00:14:07.410 --> 00:14:11.370
to the power minus 3/2.

00:14:11.370 --> 00:14:13.470
Maybe you like it that way.

00:14:13.470 --> 00:14:15.870
I'm totally OK with that.

00:14:15.870 --> 00:14:19.250
Or maybe you want
to see it as--

00:14:19.250 --> 00:14:28.310
this minus exponent
down here as 3/2.

00:14:28.310 --> 00:14:30.440
Either way, both good.

00:14:30.440 --> 00:14:34.650
OK, so that's one
more practice.

00:14:34.650 --> 00:14:37.970
and I've got one more in mind.

00:14:37.970 --> 00:14:42.310
But let me return to this board,
the starting board,

00:14:42.310 --> 00:14:50.060
just to justify where did this
chain rule come from.

00:14:50.060 --> 00:14:53.160
OK, where do derivatives
come from?

00:14:53.160 --> 00:15:00.280
Derivative always start with
small finite steps, with delta

00:15:00.280 --> 00:15:01.530
rather than d.

00:15:05.160 --> 00:15:09.630
So I start here, I make a change
in x, and I want to

00:15:09.630 --> 00:15:13.660
know the change in z.

00:15:13.660 --> 00:15:23.320
These are small, but not
zero, not darn small.

00:15:23.320 --> 00:15:30.860
OK, all right, those are true
quantities, and for those, I'm

00:15:30.860 --> 00:15:41.870
perfectly entitled to divide and
multiply by the change in

00:15:41.870 --> 00:15:44.170
y because there will
be a change in y.

00:15:44.170 --> 00:15:49.070
When I change x, that produces
a change in g of x.

00:15:49.070 --> 00:15:50.840
You remember this was the y.

00:15:54.000 --> 00:15:56.760
So this factor--

00:15:56.760 --> 00:16:00.310
well, first of all, that's
simply a true

00:16:00.310 --> 00:16:02.840
statement for fractions.

00:16:05.720 --> 00:16:07.080
But it's the right way.

00:16:07.080 --> 00:16:09.070
It's the way we want it.

00:16:09.070 --> 00:16:14.190
Because now when I show it, and
in words, it says when I

00:16:14.190 --> 00:16:19.130
change x a little, that produces
a change in y, and

00:16:19.130 --> 00:16:22.520
the change in y produces
a change in z.

00:16:22.520 --> 00:16:26.920
And it's the ratio that we're
after, the ratio between the

00:16:26.920 --> 00:16:29.190
original change and
the final change.

00:16:29.190 --> 00:16:32.130
So I just put the
inside change up

00:16:32.130 --> 00:16:34.020
and divide and multiply.

00:16:34.020 --> 00:16:37.490
OK, what am I going to do?

00:16:37.490 --> 00:16:41.940
What I always do, whatever body
does with derivatives at

00:16:41.940 --> 00:16:44.740
an instant, at a point.

00:16:44.740 --> 00:16:47.510
Let delta x go to 0.

00:16:47.510 --> 00:16:51.270
Now as delta x goes to 0, delta
y will go to 0, delta z

00:16:51.270 --> 00:16:55.650
will go to 0, and we get
a lot of zeroes over 0.

00:16:55.650 --> 00:16:59.870
That's what calculus is
prepared to live with.

00:16:59.870 --> 00:17:03.040
Because it keeps this ratio.

00:17:05.780 --> 00:17:13.050
It doesn't separately think
about 0 and then later 0.

00:17:13.050 --> 00:17:17.230
It's looking at the ratio
as things happen.

00:17:17.230 --> 00:17:19.619
And that ratio does
approach that.

00:17:19.619 --> 00:17:22.119
That was the definition
of the derivative.

00:17:22.119 --> 00:17:26.460
This ratio approaches that,
and we get the answer.

00:17:26.460 --> 00:17:31.490
This ratio approaches the
derivative we're after.

00:17:31.490 --> 00:17:34.370
That in a nutshell
is the thinking

00:17:34.370 --> 00:17:36.470
